I believe one of the main features asserts bring to the table is the ability to turn them on/off at compile time and/or runtime.  I don&#39;t think the assert keyword is intended to replace runtime error checking.  In your example below, in the first case you have control over the exception thrown, and whether an exception will be thrown.  A failed assert will always cause an AssertionError.  

Asserts are great for unit testing pre- and post-conditions and invariants during development.  They add something to Java that many other languages have had built-in for a long time.

Scott Stirling
JRun QA
Macromedia

