&gt; 
&gt; Does anyone have any development experience with the new Java 
&gt; assertion mechanism in JDK 1.4?
&gt; 
&gt; I am having problems appreciating what additional value this 
&gt; mechanism brings to the Java language.  The last project I 
&gt; was on applied many of the XP practices (test first,
&gt; unit testing).
&gt; 
&gt; When designing our classes, we would write tests (contracts) 
&gt; verifiying the functionality of our classes.  If one practices
&gt; this approach when developing, what additional benefit 
&gt; do assertions bring to the table?
&gt; 
&gt; This is the example I have been using:
&gt; 
&gt; Say we have a Math class with a sqrt routine.  We want to make it 
&gt; clear to the outside world that our routine does not handle 
&gt; negative numbers.  If I were to write this class today using standard
&gt; Java mechanisms for argument checking, the method would look 
&gt; something like this:
&gt; 
&gt; public float sqrt(float number) {
&gt; 	if (number &lt; 0) {
&gt; 	   throw IllegalArgumentException(&quot;Number can not be 
&gt; negative.&quot;);
&gt; 	}
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; If we were to make this a precondition (ala Design By Contract) the 
&gt; assertion would look something like:
&gt; 
&gt; public float sqrt(float number) {
&gt; 	assert number &lt; 0 : &quot;Number can not be negative.&quot;;
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Whats the difference?  Is one better then the other?
&gt; 
&gt; How is the &#39;assert&#39; keyword affecting the code people are writing?
&gt; 
&gt; Jonathan
